<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1866-06-06T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1866-06-06T00:00:00-05:00" n="765" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d765">
                            <head><persName type="from">Mr. Seward</persName> to <persName type="to">Mr. Bigelow</persName></head>
                            <opener>
                                <seg rendition="#left">No. 476.]</seg>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>,</placeName>
                                    <date calendar="gregorian" when="1866-06-06"><hi rend="italic">June</hi> 6, 1866.</date></dateline></opener>
                            <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir:</hi> I have the honor to acknowledge the
                                receipt of your despatch of May 25, No. 325.</p>
                            <p>The information which it contains seems to justify us in assuming
                                that the French government has made arrangements for withdrawing
                                one-third of its forces now in Mexico from that country in October.
                                The knowledge of this fact will have a tendency to quiet the public
                                mind in the United States.</p>
                            <p>I am, sir, your obedient servant,</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>WILLIAM H. SEWARD.</signed></closer>
                            <postscript>
                                <p><hi rend="smallcaps">John Bigelow</hi>, Esq., <hi rend="italic">&amp;c., &amp;c., &amp;c</hi>.</p>
                            </postscript>
                        </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>